  "publisher": "SPiER Project (FHIR translation of NIMH ASQ Toolkit)",
  "description": "FHIR Questionnaire representation of the NIMH Ask Suicide-Screening Questions (ASQ) tool. A 4-question screening instrument validated for youth (8+) and adults across ED, inpatient, outpatient, and primary care settings. Includes acuity question (#5) triggered by any positive response to questions 1-4. Source: NIMH ASQ Toolkit (www.nimh.nih.gov/research/research-conducted-at-nimh/asq-toolkit-materials).",
  "purpose": "Universal suicide risk screening. The ASQ takes approximately 20 seconds to administer and stratifies patients into Negative Screen, Non-Acute Positive Screen, or Acute Positive Screen (imminent risk). PILOT STATUS: LOINC bindings on items are candidate mappings marked with the spier-coding-verification extension set to 'unverified'. See the ASQ pilot plan in the SPiER app for the reconciliation checklist. NOTE: the ASQ has no published panel or per-item LOINC codes (verified June 2026); the root code and the five item codes use SPiER-local CodeSystems marked 'no-standard-binding'. The earlier LOINC 93373-9 panel code was the C-SSRS screener panel, not ASQ.",
  "copyright": "The ASQ is a public domain instrument developed by the National Institute of Mental Health (NIMH). No permission is required for use.",
